SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 552
By Haile
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Susan O. Binns of
Nashville.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Susan O. Binns; and
WHEREAS, Susan Binns was an extraordinary individual whose life was marked by
compassion, determination, and an unwavering commitment to helping others; and
WHEREAS, she was among the first women to receive a scholarship to Cumberland
Heights in 1979, beginning her own journey in recovery and immediately dedicating her life to
supporting others, eventually earning her licensed alcohol and drug abuse counselor
certification in 1990 and helping to start thirteen addiction care and recovery housing programs
in Nashville; and
WHEREAS, a devoted advocate for recovery and ethical standards in addiction
treatment, Ms. Binns was a pioneer in the field, founding YANA (You Are Never Alone) in 1996,
one of Nashville's first recovery housing communities for women, and offering holistic, trauma-
informed care well before those principles became standard; and
WHEREAS, in 2008, Susan Binns founded the Tennessee Alliance of Recovery
Residences, the State's first self-governing recovery housing organization, in response to the
need for safe transitional housing identified by the late Judge Seth Norman; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Binns served as national president of the Association of Halfway House
Alcoholism Programs and helped lead its evolution into the National Alliance for Recovery
Residences (NARR) in 2011, now a national standard-setting body representing over 8,000
recovery homes, including nearly 300 in Tennessee; and
WHEREAS, her work has been recognized by the Substance Abuse and Mental Health
Services Administration, the American Society of Addiction Medicine, and the National Council
for Mental Wellbeing, all of which now affirm the core practices Susan Binns championed; and
