WHEREAS, a recipient of multiple honors, including the 2024 Lifetime Achievement
Award from the Tennessee Association for Addiction Professionals, Ms. Binns also mentored
numerous leaders in the recovery community, including Trina Frierson, founder of Mending
Hearts, and many others who credit her with shaping their path and purpose; and
WHEREAS, Susan Binns was known for her tireless advocacy, her deep understanding
of trauma and recovery, her willingness to be vulnerable with those she served, and her
unmatched sense of humor, which brought laughter and healing into the spaces she helped
create; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Binns leaves behind her loving children, Chandelle C. Binns and John
J. Binns, and a host of friends, colleagues, and those in recovery who will long cherish her
memory and the lives she changed; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of Susan Binns, a woman whose tireless work on behalf of people
from all walks of life helped foster dignity, healing, and opportunity across this State; now,
therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Susan O. Binns, reflecting
fondly upon her impeccable character and her stalwart commitment to living the examined life
with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Ms. Binns.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
